WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.892 --> 00:00:07.600
LOGAN URY: So it's my
pleasure to welcome

00:00:07.600 --> 00:00:09.670
my friend, Moira, here today.

00:00:09.670 --> 00:00:12.520
And we're so lucky
to have her with us.

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:14.770
She's a writer and
academic who is currently

00:00:14.770 --> 00:00:17.080
part of the Harvard
Society of Fellows.

00:00:17.080 --> 00:00:19.550
She just finished
her PhD at Yale,

00:00:19.550 --> 00:00:22.150
so we should all
congratulate her afterwards.

00:00:22.150 --> 00:00:23.960
And her work is fascinating.

00:00:23.960 --> 00:00:27.460
It's at the intersection
of social theory,

00:00:27.460 --> 00:00:30.280
along with histories of
labor, media, and technology

00:00:30.280 --> 00:00:32.710
in the 20th and 21st centuries.

00:00:32.710 --> 00:00:34.900
Her book, which we'll
be talking about today,

00:00:34.900 --> 00:00:38.200
is called "Labor of Love,
The Invention of Dating."

00:00:38.200 --> 00:00:40.420
And Moira is also
a founding editor

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:44.020
of "Logic," which is a new
magazine about technology.

00:00:44.020 --> 00:00:45.797
Moira Weigel, thank
you for joining us.

00:00:45.797 --> 00:00:47.380
MOIRA WEIGEL: Thank
you for having me.

00:00:47.380 --> 00:00:48.350
LOGAN URY: Woo.

00:00:48.350 --> 00:00:49.030
OK.

00:00:49.030 --> 00:00:51.940
So just to kick it off, I
want to start by digging

00:00:51.940 --> 00:00:53.740
into the book.

00:00:53.740 --> 00:00:55.510
You've called the
book "Labor of Love,"

00:00:55.510 --> 00:00:58.780
secretly an economic history.

00:00:58.780 --> 00:01:02.020
What's the connection between
economic forces and dating,

00:01:02.020 --> 00:01:04.162
and how has that played
out in the last century?

00:01:04.162 --> 00:01:05.620
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah,
well, there are

00:01:05.620 --> 00:01:08.440
a lot of connections between
economic forces and dating.

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:11.590
I feel like, to backtrack
to when I was first

00:01:11.590 --> 00:01:13.990
starting to think about
the book, part of why--

00:01:13.990 --> 00:01:16.601
contrary to what it might
seem, I wasn't always obsessed

00:01:16.601 --> 00:01:18.100
with dating, or at
least not anymore

00:01:18.100 --> 00:01:21.520
than I think most
people probably are.

00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:25.240
But one aspect of its history
that really interested

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:27.850
me is that this practice
that we call dating,

00:01:27.850 --> 00:01:31.417
that we might take for granted
as sort of like natural

00:01:31.417 --> 00:01:33.250
and not think about as
something historical,

00:01:33.250 --> 00:01:35.870
is actually pretty
new in human history,

00:01:35.870 --> 00:01:37.870
if you look at most societies.

00:01:37.870 --> 00:01:40.210
It's not been the case that
young people go out and meet

00:01:40.210 --> 00:01:41.750
one another on their own.

00:01:41.750 --> 00:01:44.050
And it really only
emerges when you

00:01:44.050 --> 00:01:47.034
start to have large numbers
of women in the workforce.

00:01:47.034 --> 00:01:48.450
Dating is connected
to the economy

00:01:48.450 --> 00:01:49.700
in a number of different ways.

00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:52.033
But one of the big ways, and
part of why, as a feminist,

00:01:52.033 --> 00:01:53.650
I was excited to
write about it, is

00:01:53.650 --> 00:01:55.600
it only emerges
as a practice when

00:01:55.600 --> 00:01:58.150
you have large numbers of
women going outside the home,

00:01:58.150 --> 00:02:00.340
going outside private
space into public space,

00:02:00.340 --> 00:02:03.010
earning their own money,
and taking control

00:02:03.010 --> 00:02:05.530
of their own romantic
and sexual lives

00:02:05.530 --> 00:02:08.259
in a way that really was
pretty unprecedented.

00:02:08.259 --> 00:02:11.080
I mean, it's quite interesting,
because of course, this

00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:13.400
happens differently-- my
book's mostly about America.

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:17.560
But we can watch this happen
in Asia in a different way,

00:02:17.560 --> 00:02:19.070
or in Africa in a different way.

00:02:19.070 --> 00:02:21.760
But the history of dating
is very tied to the history

00:02:21.760 --> 00:02:23.384
of women entering paid work.

00:02:23.384 --> 00:02:25.550
And then, of course, there
are some other ways, too.

00:02:25.550 --> 00:02:28.210
I think that the ways we
think about love and romance

00:02:28.210 --> 00:02:32.320
are totally shaped, in a
number of ways, by the way

00:02:32.320 --> 00:02:34.770
we think about
economics, in terms

00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:37.056
of being on the market, off
the market, hard to get.

00:02:37.056 --> 00:02:38.430
These are all
economic metaphors.

00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:41.310
So I think there's a kind of
economic unconscious to how

00:02:41.310 --> 00:02:44.134
we think of a lot of
things about dating.

00:02:44.134 --> 00:02:45.050
LOGAN URY: Absolutely.

00:02:45.050 --> 00:02:48.040
So how has today's
economy reflected itself

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:51.190
in this age of Tinder?

00:02:51.190 --> 00:02:54.880
MOIRA WEIGEL: What's the gig,
the sexual gig economy like?

00:02:54.880 --> 00:02:59.830
I think that, like every
other aspect of our lives,

00:02:59.830 --> 00:03:03.730
our romantic and sexual lives
are becoming more flexible.

00:03:03.730 --> 00:03:06.864
And this has both positive
and negative aspects.

00:03:06.864 --> 00:03:08.530
I feel like one reason
I wanted to write

00:03:08.530 --> 00:03:11.560
the book was to push back
against all these kind of doom

00:03:11.560 --> 00:03:15.460
and gloom narratives about
dating apps and online dating.

00:03:15.460 --> 00:03:18.862
I feel like around 2012, 2013,
when I was first starting--

00:03:18.862 --> 00:03:20.445
2013, 2014-- when I
was first starting

00:03:20.445 --> 00:03:22.240
to think about these
questions, there

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:25.180
were a series of high
profile stories and books.

00:03:25.180 --> 00:03:27.970
And I know that folks had
moms send these to them,

00:03:27.970 --> 00:03:29.200
or saw them in another way.

00:03:29.200 --> 00:03:32.590
But there was this
big end of men story

00:03:32.590 --> 00:03:33.730
that was in "The Atlantic."

00:03:33.730 --> 00:03:35.740
There was a huge "New
York Times" story

00:03:35.740 --> 00:03:37.270
called "The End of Courtship."

00:03:37.270 --> 00:03:40.910
There was all this anxiety
about hookup culture.

00:03:40.910 --> 00:03:44.057
And I'm always interested
in these conversations

00:03:44.057 --> 00:03:46.390
about crisis, because I think
it's where people actually

00:03:46.390 --> 00:03:49.960
articulate what they believe men
should be and women should be.

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:52.510
So I'm always very
suspicious of them.

00:03:52.510 --> 00:03:54.832
But at that time, anyway,
I was interested in all

00:03:54.832 --> 00:03:56.290
these articles that
were basically,

00:03:56.290 --> 00:04:00.670
like, humans have always met
and fallen in love in this way.

00:04:00.670 --> 00:04:02.260
And ever since
caveman days, this

00:04:02.260 --> 00:04:04.510
is how men and women
were until Tinder.

00:04:04.510 --> 00:04:06.190
And now everything's over.

00:04:06.190 --> 00:04:08.650
This, as a historian
and as a young person

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:11.330
who was still dating, this
seemed suspicious to me.

00:04:11.330 --> 00:04:13.210
So part of why I wanted
to do this research

00:04:13.210 --> 00:04:15.847
was, I was, like, well, it
can't really be the end of sex

00:04:15.847 --> 00:04:17.430
and the end of men
and the end of love

00:04:17.430 --> 00:04:20.620
and the end of courtship
all because of Tinder.

00:04:20.620 --> 00:04:22.150
So what's behind that?

00:04:22.150 --> 00:04:24.910
So anyway, that was
wanting to push back

00:04:24.910 --> 00:04:27.550
against that narrative of
crisis around courtship

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:29.374
was part of how I got
into this project.

00:04:29.374 --> 00:04:30.040
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:04:30.040 --> 00:04:32.140
That's something that really
fascinated me about the book.

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:34.556
It felt like there were these
moments of crisis every time

00:04:34.556 --> 00:04:35.741
there was new technology.

00:04:35.741 --> 00:04:37.490
And I actually found
it pretty comforting.

00:04:37.490 --> 00:04:39.632
So you talked in
the book about how,

00:04:39.632 --> 00:04:41.590
when the automobile came
out, people were like,

00:04:41.590 --> 00:04:42.850
this is the end of morality.

00:04:42.850 --> 00:04:44.800
And at these different
stages, people

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:46.120
had this moral hand-wringing.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:48.010
So I would love if
you could talk us

00:04:48.010 --> 00:04:49.420
through some of those moments.

00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:51.700
And then also tell
us, is there even

00:04:51.700 --> 00:04:53.950
such thing as traditional
courtship, this idea

00:04:53.950 --> 00:04:56.260
that people seem to
think is being lost,

00:04:56.260 --> 00:04:58.045
is that even
something that exists?

00:04:58.045 --> 00:04:59.170
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yes, totally.

00:04:59.170 --> 00:05:00.790
So this will either
be really comforting

00:05:00.790 --> 00:05:02.740
or really depressing, depending
how you think about it.

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:04.960
But one of the interesting
things about the history

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:08.277
of dating is that-- and to
talk about it, by the way,

00:05:08.277 --> 00:05:08.860
people often--

00:05:08.860 --> 00:05:11.110
I call it, in the subtitle,
"The Invention of Dating,"

00:05:11.110 --> 00:05:12.280
and people are like,
well, what does that mean?

00:05:12.280 --> 00:05:13.446
Haven't people always dated?

00:05:13.446 --> 00:05:16.042
And I joke that dating
was invented in 1896.

00:05:16.042 --> 00:05:17.500
It is the first
time that we see it

00:05:17.500 --> 00:05:19.990
in the print record being used--

00:05:19.990 --> 00:05:22.180
that word, in the way
that we use it now.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:24.410
But basically, and again,
as I was saying earlier,

00:05:24.410 --> 00:05:27.730
it's tied to women entering
the workplace and young people

00:05:27.730 --> 00:05:31.060
in general moving to cities and
this new kind of urban culture

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:33.220
that you have emerging
in that period.

00:05:33.220 --> 00:05:35.787
But when you go back
into the history,

00:05:35.787 --> 00:05:37.870
the thing that is either
comforting or depressing,

00:05:37.870 --> 00:05:39.245
depending how you
think about it,

00:05:39.245 --> 00:05:42.850
is there has never been any
time or place in which people

00:05:42.850 --> 00:05:45.160
are, like, dating,
great, killing it,

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:46.527
I'm sure I'm doing it right.

00:05:46.527 --> 00:05:47.860
All the kids are doing it right.

00:05:47.860 --> 00:05:49.360
We're not worried
about them at all.

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:51.460
It's constantly, from
the very beginning

00:05:51.460 --> 00:05:55.520
of dating, dating is said
to be dying or in crisis.

00:05:55.520 --> 00:05:57.340
And one of my favorite
research things

00:05:57.340 --> 00:05:59.256
is that I learned that
during the first decade

00:05:59.256 --> 00:06:00.970
or so that you have
women going out

00:06:00.970 --> 00:06:04.570
with men on what we would
now think of as the most

00:06:04.570 --> 00:06:07.000
traditional looking kind of
date, like going out to dinner

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:10.240
or going out to a movie, that
the person who would do this

00:06:10.240 --> 00:06:13.049
are often arrested on
prostitution charges.

00:06:13.049 --> 00:06:14.590
And a lot of the
early research I did

00:06:14.590 --> 00:06:16.780
was in, like, vice squad
reports, because there

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:20.140
was no precedent for women
going out on their own

00:06:20.140 --> 00:06:24.490
with men, or for money being
transacted in courtship.

00:06:24.490 --> 00:06:26.470
When you think of a
Jane Austen novel,

00:06:26.470 --> 00:06:28.270
Mr. Darcy isn't buying anything.

00:06:28.270 --> 00:06:29.740
He's just going
to her living room

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:31.250
and hanging out with her mom--

00:06:31.250 --> 00:06:33.370
Elizabeth Bennett,
that's her name.

00:06:33.370 --> 00:06:36.352
So anyway, I think that back
in the very beginning, the very

00:06:36.352 --> 00:06:38.560
first period where you have
this thing called dating,

00:06:38.560 --> 00:06:41.800
you have not just hand-wringing,
but literally arrests

00:06:41.800 --> 00:06:43.794
and people being dragged
off to reformatory.

00:06:43.794 --> 00:06:45.460
And then throughout
the history, there's

00:06:45.460 --> 00:06:48.632
this constant kind of
overtone of anxiety,

00:06:48.632 --> 00:06:50.590
both from the grown ups
and from the people who

00:06:50.590 --> 00:06:51.730
are participating in dating.

00:06:51.730 --> 00:06:53.354
Because one thing
that's distinctive is

00:06:53.354 --> 00:06:54.280
nobody ever knows--

00:06:54.280 --> 00:06:56.140
unlike courtships
systems, where it's

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:59.410
controlled by parents or by
rabbis or priests or whomever--

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:02.020
a defining feature of dating is
that nobody knows exactly how

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:03.230
you're supposed to do it.

00:07:03.230 --> 00:07:04.710
And that's always been true.

00:07:04.710 --> 00:07:04.990
LOGAN URY: Right.

00:07:04.990 --> 00:07:06.310
So let's paint a
picture for people

00:07:06.310 --> 00:07:07.393
who haven't read the book.

00:07:07.393 --> 00:07:08.920
What came before dating?

00:07:08.920 --> 00:07:09.940
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah.

00:07:09.940 --> 00:07:12.010
So in the book, of
course, everywhere

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:15.700
has their own variables
and their own situations.

00:07:15.700 --> 00:07:17.560
But the dominant
middle class system

00:07:17.560 --> 00:07:21.220
of courtship in the 19th
century is called calling.

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:23.830
And again, it's the Jane
Austen scenario, right?

00:07:23.830 --> 00:07:25.027
You sit in your living room.

00:07:25.027 --> 00:07:26.860
Your mom, your aunt,
your sisters are there.

00:07:26.860 --> 00:07:29.874
Gentlemen callers
can come visit you.

00:07:29.874 --> 00:07:31.540
It's almost-- and
since I'm an academic,

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:34.640
I always think of it as a kind
of awkward, like, office hours,

00:07:34.640 --> 00:07:35.765
romantic kind of situation.

00:07:35.765 --> 00:07:37.306
LOGAN URY: No one
ever goes to those.

00:07:37.306 --> 00:07:37.856
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:37.856 --> 00:07:39.180
MOIRA WEIGEL: They do.

00:07:39.180 --> 00:07:41.650
No one wants to come
to my office hours.

00:07:41.650 --> 00:07:45.790
But yeah, so calling it
as a system of courtship

00:07:45.790 --> 00:07:47.427
is symbolically important.

00:07:47.427 --> 00:07:49.510
I mean, I believe that all
of our social practices

00:07:49.510 --> 00:07:52.090
encode all kinds of
beliefs about how

00:07:52.090 --> 00:07:55.617
we think the world works
and what kinds of rules

00:07:55.617 --> 00:07:56.950
different people should perform.

00:07:56.950 --> 00:07:59.690
But it locates courtship
in the home, right?

00:07:59.690 --> 00:08:01.650
So it's in the
territory of the family.

00:08:01.650 --> 00:08:03.310
It's being supervised.

00:08:03.310 --> 00:08:05.050
It is supposed to
be non-economic.

00:08:05.050 --> 00:08:06.310
No money is exchanged.

00:08:06.310 --> 00:08:08.018
I mean, the thing
that's very interesting

00:08:08.018 --> 00:08:10.300
is that it's also
very much understood

00:08:10.300 --> 00:08:12.590
to be in control of the women.

00:08:12.590 --> 00:08:16.030
I read-- there's an advice
column in "The Ladies Home

00:08:16.030 --> 00:08:18.730
Journal," which is the
most popular magazine

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:20.620
in the world around 1900.

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:22.720
And there's an advice
columnist called the Lady

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:27.520
from Philadelphia, who answers
people's romantic questions.

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:30.440
And she would get these letters
from young men saying, oh,

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:33.919
can I go call on a young woman
if she hasn't invited me?

00:08:33.919 --> 00:08:36.721
And the Lady from Philadelphia,
contrary to our belief

00:08:36.721 --> 00:08:38.179
that men are always
the initiators,

00:08:38.179 --> 00:08:39.076
says absolutely not.

00:08:39.076 --> 00:08:39.909
You know, you can't.

00:08:39.909 --> 00:08:40.799
If a woman doesn't
want to see you,

00:08:40.799 --> 00:08:42.924
you can't go show up at
her house in this way.

00:08:42.924 --> 00:08:44.590
So there's this
important sense in which

00:08:44.590 --> 00:08:49.150
the calling system makes women
like the hosts of courtship.

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:51.920
And this dramatically
changes when

00:08:51.920 --> 00:08:54.910
courtship moves from the
living room, with mom and dad,

00:08:54.910 --> 00:08:56.920
into the public sphere,
which historically

00:08:56.920 --> 00:08:59.530
has been seen as the sphere
of men, the sphere of money,

00:08:59.530 --> 00:09:01.136
the sphere of the market.

00:09:01.136 --> 00:09:03.010
LOGAN URY: So it's the
predecessor to Bumble.

00:09:03.010 --> 00:09:04.480
Women have to make
the first move?

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:05.896
MOIRA WEIGEL:
Something like that.

00:09:05.896 --> 00:09:08.470
Think about it-- if
your mom were on Bumble,

00:09:08.470 --> 00:09:10.312
watching [INAUDIBLE], maybe.

00:09:10.312 --> 00:09:11.020
LOGAN URY: Great.

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:12.728
So we'll talk about
that in a little bit,

00:09:12.728 --> 00:09:14.860
in terms of these
ideas that we think

00:09:14.860 --> 00:09:19.210
are deep seated into our DNA,
and actually are relatively new

00:09:19.210 --> 00:09:20.260
inventions.

00:09:20.260 --> 00:09:23.170
So one thing I read was that
you had initially thought

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:25.000
of things like dating
and relationships

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:29.440
as maybe too silly or trivial
to warrant serious study.

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:32.440
How did you change and
come to write this book?

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:33.940
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah,
well, this book,

00:09:33.940 --> 00:09:35.980
as my PhD supervisor would
be happy to tell you,

00:09:35.980 --> 00:09:38.260
was a distraction from
my main PhD research.

00:09:38.260 --> 00:09:40.930
It wasn't what I was supposed
to be working on at Yale, where

00:09:40.930 --> 00:09:42.650
I was in grad school.

00:09:42.650 --> 00:09:44.952
I feel like, again,
about this time when

00:09:44.952 --> 00:09:46.660
there were all these
stories coming out--

00:09:46.660 --> 00:09:48.390
which I see, in a
way, as a reaction

00:09:48.390 --> 00:09:49.390
to the financial crisis.

00:09:49.390 --> 00:09:51.681
I mean, we could have a longer
conversation about this,

00:09:51.681 --> 00:09:55.180
but why around 2013, 2014, there
was all this anxiety in the air

00:09:55.180 --> 00:09:57.615
about men aren't
acting like men,

00:09:57.615 --> 00:09:59.990
and women aren't-- you know,
kids aren't dating properly.

00:09:59.990 --> 00:10:03.400
But in that moment,
I was in grad school.

00:10:03.400 --> 00:10:05.650
I was getting trained in
all these ways of looking

00:10:05.650 --> 00:10:06.597
at theory and history.

00:10:06.597 --> 00:10:08.680
But of course, on my own
time, I spent all my time

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:11.440
with my friends talking about
love and sex and romancing,

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:13.390
not all of it, but
quite a lot of it.

00:10:13.390 --> 00:10:16.300
And I feel as if I came to
this point where I realized,

00:10:16.300 --> 00:10:19.700
we're all developing these huge
intellectual tool kits to look

00:10:19.700 --> 00:10:21.820
at certain kinds of questions.

00:10:21.820 --> 00:10:26.530
But why don't we take this other
kind of question seriously?

00:10:26.530 --> 00:10:29.830
And I think, in a very
deep way, you know,

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:33.490
dating, for better or worse, is
the system that our culture has

00:10:33.490 --> 00:10:38.350
in place for reproducing the
world, forming social bonds,

00:10:38.350 --> 00:10:40.150
for entering biological
reproduction,

00:10:40.150 --> 00:10:42.070
for setting up kinship networks.

00:10:42.070 --> 00:10:45.460
There's very little that's more
serious than that, actually.

00:10:45.460 --> 00:10:50.020
And I think that there's
actually something

00:10:50.020 --> 00:10:53.770
really kind of sexist and
conservative about treating

00:10:53.770 --> 00:10:55.420
some of these topics
as if they don't

00:10:55.420 --> 00:10:58.370
warrant serious
intellectual consideration.

00:10:58.370 --> 00:11:00.280
I mean, I think it's
kind of funny to have

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:01.930
this whole cultural
system, especially

00:11:01.930 --> 00:11:03.971
if you're a straight woman,
where you've grown up

00:11:03.971 --> 00:11:06.280
your whole life with
magazines and movies and books

00:11:06.280 --> 00:11:09.769
and all of these cultural
signals telling you here's

00:11:09.769 --> 00:11:11.560
what you should want,
here's how you should

00:11:11.560 --> 00:11:13.476
be if you want to be
loved, which, by the way,

00:11:13.476 --> 00:11:15.550
is the most important
thing about you.

00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:17.950
And then the minute
that you're, like,

00:11:17.950 --> 00:11:19.210
I have a question about that.

00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:20.540
It's like, it's not serious.

00:11:20.540 --> 00:11:23.080
Don't waste serious intellectual
energy looking at this.

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:25.210
So I feel as if I
came to the project

00:11:25.210 --> 00:11:27.700
kind of extracurricularly
in graduate school.

00:11:27.700 --> 00:11:31.000
But then once I started thinking
about it and all the ways

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:35.620
that our romantic
beliefs are enmeshed

00:11:35.620 --> 00:11:38.380
in deep social beliefs,
historical practices, that kind

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:41.390
of thing, I really felt,
it felt important to take

00:11:41.390 --> 00:11:43.570
a serious intellectual
lens to look

00:11:43.570 --> 00:11:45.820
at the sources of these
messages and the work

00:11:45.820 --> 00:11:48.640
that they were doing in terms
of teaching us to desire.

00:11:48.640 --> 00:11:50.230
LOGAN URY: Well, I'm so
glad you did write the book.

00:11:50.230 --> 00:11:50.790
MOIRA WEIGEL: Oh, thank you.

00:11:50.790 --> 00:11:52.180
LOGAN URY: And I
was wondering if you

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:53.510
would read this passage for us.

00:11:53.510 --> 00:11:53.681
MOIRA WEIGEL: Oh, dear.

00:11:53.681 --> 00:11:54.181
Sure.

00:11:54.181 --> 00:11:56.950
LOGAN URY: And then I have
a follow up question on it.

00:11:56.950 --> 00:11:58.720
MOIRA WEIGEL: Ooh.

00:11:58.720 --> 00:12:00.310
Look at this.

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:01.645
All right.

00:12:01.645 --> 00:12:04.090
I began to feel a need
to write this book when

00:12:04.090 --> 00:12:07.780
I sensed that I was trying to
make a life according to rules

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:11.590
I did not understand and that
the process had blinded me

00:12:11.590 --> 00:12:13.660
to my desires.

00:12:13.660 --> 00:12:16.970
Following my desires was
supposed to be the point.

00:12:16.970 --> 00:12:18.970
Yet I had never
reflected long enough

00:12:18.970 --> 00:12:21.700
to discover whether the
feelings that I believe

00:12:21.700 --> 00:12:24.580
should be there actually were.

00:12:24.580 --> 00:12:27.070
I had no idea who I was.

00:12:27.070 --> 00:12:28.990
And as long as I
kept impersonating

00:12:28.990 --> 00:12:31.030
all the women I
thought I should be,

00:12:31.030 --> 00:12:34.150
I could not receive
love, much less give it.

00:12:34.150 --> 00:12:38.825
I had no self to
choose to give it from.

00:12:38.825 --> 00:12:41.162
True story.

00:12:41.162 --> 00:12:42.620
So if you ever feel
moved to laugh,

00:12:42.620 --> 00:12:44.286
or it seems like I'm
trying to be funny,

00:12:44.286 --> 00:12:45.892
just, like, feel free.

00:12:45.892 --> 00:12:47.350
LOGAN URY: So based
on that passage

00:12:47.350 --> 00:12:50.050
and based on what you know
now, I'd love to ask you

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:53.350
what advice would you
give 16-year-old Moira?

00:12:53.350 --> 00:12:56.290
And more broadly, if
you could design a class

00:12:56.290 --> 00:12:58.810
that every high school
girl had to take

00:12:58.810 --> 00:13:01.050
before entering
adult relationships,

00:13:01.050 --> 00:13:02.770
what would you include
in that course?

00:13:02.770 --> 00:13:04.990
MOIRA WEIGEL: OK, these
are big questions.

00:13:04.990 --> 00:13:08.030
I think-- and I'd be very
curious to hear from people

00:13:08.030 --> 00:13:08.530
here--

00:13:08.530 --> 00:13:10.071
I think what's
interesting, if you're

00:13:10.071 --> 00:13:14.410
a certain kind of ambitious,
Type A, high achieving,

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:17.050
straight woman especially,
you receive this one set

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:18.342
of messages about your career.

00:13:18.342 --> 00:13:19.800
And you're supposed
to be confident

00:13:19.800 --> 00:13:22.133
and you're supposed to be
able to act in all these ways.

00:13:22.133 --> 00:13:24.336
And then you receive,
basically, opposite messages

00:13:24.336 --> 00:13:25.210
about your love life.

00:13:25.210 --> 00:13:27.940
And indeed, not only are you
not supposed to show initiative,

00:13:27.940 --> 00:13:31.690
you're supposed to do all this
extra work to cover up the fact

00:13:31.690 --> 00:13:33.700
that you have those traits.

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:35.800
So I feel as if--

00:13:35.800 --> 00:13:39.760
I mean, 16-year-old Moira, who
knows what could have helped.

00:13:39.760 --> 00:13:45.710
But if I could have known
anything earlier, I think--

00:13:45.710 --> 00:13:48.530
I don't know, I would
have liked to be

00:13:48.530 --> 00:13:53.081
more aware of the ways
in which these rules that

00:13:53.081 --> 00:13:55.580
are given to us and these things
that we're taught about how

00:13:55.580 --> 00:14:00.440
to be if we want to be desirable
serve all these incentives that

00:14:00.440 --> 00:14:01.730
are not necessarily our own.

00:14:01.730 --> 00:14:03.800
It's an excellent way
to sell women things.

00:14:03.800 --> 00:14:06.590
Like, anxiety-- it's, like, tell
a woman that something that she

00:14:06.590 --> 00:14:09.067
didn't even know was a
thing is wrong with her,

00:14:09.067 --> 00:14:10.650
and then sell her
the thing to fix it.

00:14:10.650 --> 00:14:13.850
It's like an engine of quite a
lot of the economy in general.

00:14:13.850 --> 00:14:18.750
But I feel as if, yeah,
this way in which you

00:14:18.750 --> 00:14:22.460
get so many messages that are
also always about repressing

00:14:22.460 --> 00:14:23.420
your own feelings.

00:14:23.420 --> 00:14:25.836
If you think, and we can talk
about this, but if you think

00:14:25.836 --> 00:14:28.070
about how many self-help
franchises are basically,

00:14:28.070 --> 00:14:30.350
like, whatever you
might feel like doing,

00:14:30.350 --> 00:14:31.400
do the opposite thing.

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:32.140
Don't do that.

00:14:32.140 --> 00:14:33.181
Don't show your feelings.

00:14:33.181 --> 00:14:34.820
Don't express your desires.

00:14:34.820 --> 00:14:38.570
I think being aware of the
ways in which that grows out

00:14:38.570 --> 00:14:40.871
of history that's
deeply sexist and serves

00:14:40.871 --> 00:14:42.620
institutions and
practices that are deeply

00:14:42.620 --> 00:14:46.190
sexist would have been
helpful and probably would

00:14:46.190 --> 00:14:50.580
have made me less anxious and
self-hated in various moments.

00:14:50.580 --> 00:14:52.314
What was the other
thing, a syllabus?

00:14:52.314 --> 00:14:54.480
LOGAN URY: Yeah, I mean,
it's kind of a combination.

00:14:54.480 --> 00:14:55.880
It's like, what would
16-year-old Moira

00:14:55.880 --> 00:14:58.070
have benefited from knowing
with what you know now?

00:14:58.070 --> 00:15:00.278
But what would women in
general benefit from knowing?

00:15:00.278 --> 00:15:01.657
And I think the
answer of just be

00:15:01.657 --> 00:15:03.740
skeptical of somebody
telling you that something's

00:15:03.740 --> 00:15:05.490
wrong with you and
then trying to sell you

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:07.850
something to fix it is
good advice for all of us.

00:15:07.850 --> 00:15:08.780
MOIRA WEIGEL: And I think also--

00:15:08.780 --> 00:15:10.946
and it's hard for us to do,
and it's especially hard

00:15:10.946 --> 00:15:13.220
to do in romance, because
we all have so much at stake

00:15:13.220 --> 00:15:15.110
personally and want
to make things work--

00:15:15.110 --> 00:15:18.770
but also to think structurally
and systemically sometimes

00:15:18.770 --> 00:15:20.280
can be very helpful.

00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:22.700
But I think that this is the
opposite of what we usually

00:15:22.700 --> 00:15:23.570
want from self-help.

00:15:23.570 --> 00:15:26.210
Usually, what we want is a
totally normal fair thing

00:15:26.210 --> 00:15:26.960
to want--

00:15:26.960 --> 00:15:29.030
is we're, like, what
are the 10 tricks that

00:15:29.030 --> 00:15:31.490
will help me navigate
this situation, you know,

00:15:31.490 --> 00:15:33.320
whether it's
professional or personal.

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:37.130
But I think that what is
exciting and radicalizing and

00:15:37.130 --> 00:15:38.750
liberating about
studying history

00:15:38.750 --> 00:15:42.080
is you see how many of
these issues and problems

00:15:42.080 --> 00:15:45.620
are, in fact,
structural and social.

00:15:45.620 --> 00:15:48.920
And there's quite
a lot of work left

00:15:48.920 --> 00:15:51.290
to do before women are
romantic equals, or equals

00:15:51.290 --> 00:15:54.840
of any kind, in all kinds
of social situations,

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:56.450
substantively and meaningfully.

00:15:56.450 --> 00:15:59.840
And those solutions can't all
be done by working on yourself

00:15:59.840 --> 00:16:00.470
personally.

00:16:00.470 --> 00:16:01.520
LOGAN URY: Is that
a real pep talk

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:02.870
that you've given your
friends, where they're, like,

00:16:02.870 --> 00:16:04.040
what's wrong with me?

00:16:04.040 --> 00:16:06.206
And then you're,
like, it's not you.

00:16:06.206 --> 00:16:09.800
It's market forces and
society and 100 years

00:16:09.800 --> 00:16:12.170
of sexist institutions
that have contributed

00:16:12.170 --> 00:16:13.640
to where you are today.

00:16:13.640 --> 00:16:18.970
MOIRA WEIGEL: More than 100.

00:16:18.970 --> 00:16:23.820
I think that I have--

00:16:23.820 --> 00:16:26.490
trying to think of specific
friend and specific pep talks.

00:16:26.490 --> 00:16:29.550
I mean, I think this sense in
which the answer that we get

00:16:29.550 --> 00:16:31.980
is so often work a little
harder on yourself, do

00:16:31.980 --> 00:16:33.600
a little bit more about this.

00:16:33.600 --> 00:16:35.760
I think that the idea
that it's that's not,

00:16:35.760 --> 00:16:38.160
the problem isn't always
you, is certainly a thing

00:16:38.160 --> 00:16:40.230
that I've stressed to friends.

00:16:40.230 --> 00:16:42.700
Whether I talk about market
forces when comforting

00:16:42.700 --> 00:16:45.874
a friend, I hope I don't.

00:16:45.874 --> 00:16:47.790
LOGAN URY: So I want to
talk a little bit more

00:16:47.790 --> 00:16:49.961
about what you mentioned
about self-help books.

00:16:49.961 --> 00:16:51.960
So you make this really
great point in your book

00:16:51.960 --> 00:16:54.750
that if you go to a
bookstore and you walk down

00:16:54.750 --> 00:16:57.480
the self-help aisle, on your
left-hand side you might see

00:16:57.480 --> 00:17:00.060
all the career books
that tell you lean in,

00:17:00.060 --> 00:17:02.550
work harder, don't
speak with uptalk.

00:17:02.550 --> 00:17:04.859
And it's all about
really putting effort

00:17:04.859 --> 00:17:05.808
in toward your career.

00:17:05.808 --> 00:17:07.349
And then on the
right-hand side could

00:17:07.349 --> 00:17:09.098
be all of these books
about your love life

00:17:09.098 --> 00:17:11.490
that say, whatever you want
to do, do the opposite.

00:17:11.490 --> 00:17:11.990
And--

00:17:11.990 --> 00:17:13.020
MOIRA WEIGEL: It's
not him, it's you.

00:17:13.020 --> 00:17:15.660
LOGAN URY: Yeah, I think I'll
quote you here, when you said,

00:17:15.660 --> 00:17:16.951
if you want to call him, don't.

00:17:16.951 --> 00:17:18.540
If you want to sleep
with him, don't.

00:17:18.540 --> 00:17:20.956
If you slept with him and you
want to call him afterwards,

00:17:20.956 --> 00:17:22.410
don't.

00:17:22.410 --> 00:17:23.250
And it's true.

00:17:23.250 --> 00:17:25.800
MOIRA WEIGEL: It's like the
rules is literally 32 chapters,

00:17:25.800 --> 00:17:27.750
each one of which is, like,
don't do this thing that you

00:17:27.750 --> 00:17:28.410
want to do.

00:17:28.410 --> 00:17:29.118
LOGAN URY: Right.

00:17:29.118 --> 00:17:31.980
So I think it's fascinating to
just explore how on one hand,

00:17:31.980 --> 00:17:33.960
we're being told to
put so much effort in,

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:36.420
and on the other hand,
we're told to be passive.

00:17:36.420 --> 00:17:38.970
So how do you
navigate that tension?

00:17:38.970 --> 00:17:39.720
MOIRA WEIGEL: Wow.

00:17:39.720 --> 00:17:40.740
It's a big question.

00:17:40.740 --> 00:17:42.990
I mean, I think that,
again, to look to history,

00:17:42.990 --> 00:17:44.850
a thing that interests me is
to go back to the beginning

00:17:44.850 --> 00:17:47.141
when we were saying how this
whole phenomenon of dating

00:17:47.141 --> 00:17:49.410
is predicated on women
being in the workforce,

00:17:49.410 --> 00:17:52.590
being mobile in cities,
having certain kinds of agency

00:17:52.590 --> 00:17:55.060
that we haven't had
historically, that it's then

00:17:55.060 --> 00:17:57.300
that you start to see all
this romantic advice as

00:17:57.300 --> 00:17:59.010
almost like a
reaction or an attempt

00:17:59.010 --> 00:18:02.550
to control female sexuality,
given that it's no longer being

00:18:02.550 --> 00:18:05.580
controlled by mom and dad
and the rabbi or the priest.

00:18:05.580 --> 00:18:08.450
I think that-- sorry--

00:18:08.450 --> 00:18:12.450
I think that that perspective
was very interesting to get

00:18:12.450 --> 00:18:13.730
while researching the book.

00:18:13.730 --> 00:18:16.380
It was fun to look at 19th
century advice, advice

00:18:16.380 --> 00:18:19.620
for calling, because people
were also anxious about calling.

00:18:19.620 --> 00:18:22.657
But there wasn't this
emphasis on deceit.

00:18:22.657 --> 00:18:24.240
I feel like in
contemporary self-help,

00:18:24.240 --> 00:18:26.520
there's so much emphasis--
and I mean this, by the way,

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:27.353
for straight people.

00:18:27.353 --> 00:18:29.964
Fascinatingly, self-help for
queer people is very different,

00:18:29.964 --> 00:18:31.380
and I think shows
how much of this

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:34.900
is about reinforcing certain
binary gender roles, actually.

00:18:34.900 --> 00:18:37.860
But there's so much
emphasis on not

00:18:37.860 --> 00:18:40.140
showing too much
about how you feel

00:18:40.140 --> 00:18:43.040
or covering up your desire.

00:18:43.040 --> 00:18:45.150
And this really only
emerges with dating.

00:18:45.150 --> 00:18:47.130
In this earlier era,
there's much more

00:18:47.130 --> 00:18:49.680
emphasis on sort of
sincere self-expression

00:18:49.680 --> 00:18:51.000
and straightforwardness.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:53.980
And I think that in a lot of
ways, from a macro perspective,

00:18:53.980 --> 00:18:56.430
this is about controlling
female sexuality

00:18:56.430 --> 00:19:00.210
and how anxious it makes a
culture broadly for women

00:19:00.210 --> 00:19:02.717
to have certain kinds of
liberties that they hadn't had.

00:19:02.717 --> 00:19:05.050
LOGAN URY: And also, if you
tell women men are from Mars

00:19:05.050 --> 00:19:06.840
and women are from
Venus, it's a lot easier

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:08.820
to sell both of them a book
to explain the other gender.

00:19:08.820 --> 00:19:10.320
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah,
exactly, I feel,

00:19:10.320 --> 00:19:13.410
like, very, very many self-help
books can kind of be summarized

00:19:13.410 --> 00:19:17.550
as, what dudes are like, by
a dude, what women are really

00:19:17.550 --> 00:19:18.370
like, by a woman.

00:19:18.370 --> 00:19:20.940
That this sort of
mutual mystification

00:19:20.940 --> 00:19:23.160
of men and women to each
other is a very good engine

00:19:23.160 --> 00:19:24.872
for selling both sides things.

00:19:24.872 --> 00:19:26.580
LOGAN URY: So this
whole idea about women

00:19:26.580 --> 00:19:28.890
need to be passive in
dating, it's often chalked up

00:19:28.890 --> 00:19:30.780
to this evolutionary legacy.

00:19:30.780 --> 00:19:32.520
Can you talk a
little bit about that

00:19:32.520 --> 00:19:35.670
and where some of that
pseudo science emerges from,

00:19:35.670 --> 00:19:37.479
and how that impacts us today?

00:19:37.479 --> 00:19:38.270
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah.

00:19:38.270 --> 00:19:40.145
Well, I think, I don't
know, have folks seen,

00:19:40.145 --> 00:19:42.390
I feel like maybe this
trend has peaked and gone

00:19:42.390 --> 00:19:43.140
down a little bit.

00:19:43.140 --> 00:19:46.110
But I feel like the
[? ev ?] site click bait,

00:19:46.110 --> 00:19:48.420
the article that's
