00:20:29.950 --> 00:20:32.850
But it's like there's still
this idea that heterosexuality

00:20:32.850 --> 00:20:36.810
is this depressing truce
whereby women give as little sex

00:20:36.810 --> 00:20:39.330
as they can get away
with for affection,

00:20:39.330 --> 00:20:42.450
and that men do the opposite
or the contrapositive,

00:20:42.450 --> 00:20:45.240
whatever the mirror
image of that is.

00:20:45.240 --> 00:20:48.390
I think that it's
very comforting

00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:51.990
to believe that
certain phenomena are

00:20:51.990 --> 00:20:54.840
natural or biological
or are hardwired in,

00:20:54.840 --> 00:20:56.970
like the Pleistocene era.

00:20:56.970 --> 00:20:58.115
And we all love--

00:20:58.115 --> 00:21:00.490
we don't, I don't, I love
carbohydrates-- but many people

00:21:00.490 --> 00:21:04.640
love Paleo diets, or this idea
that something was natural

00:21:04.640 --> 00:21:07.560
and it's how cave people did
it, so it's how we should do it.

00:21:07.560 --> 00:21:10.860
I think that this is very
rarely a useful framework

00:21:10.860 --> 00:21:12.750
for explaining human behavior.

00:21:12.750 --> 00:21:13.860
We're social creatures.

00:21:13.860 --> 00:21:16.230
We're historical creatures.

00:21:16.230 --> 00:21:18.030
This isn't just some
wishy-washy kind

00:21:18.030 --> 00:21:19.350
of social construction thing.

00:21:19.350 --> 00:21:22.540
Brain scientists talk about
the plasticity of the brain

00:21:22.540 --> 00:21:24.330
and how quickly it can change.

00:21:24.330 --> 00:21:26.560
Scholars of gene expression
talk about how much

00:21:26.560 --> 00:21:29.887
environmental factors
trigger and shape which genes

00:21:29.887 --> 00:21:30.970
express themselves or not.

00:21:30.970 --> 00:21:35.020
So this idea that the
nature of heterosexuality

00:21:35.020 --> 00:21:38.170
was established by cave people
and we're still somehow acting

00:21:38.170 --> 00:21:42.580
that out, always to me
seemed very circular

00:21:42.580 --> 00:21:43.570
in all sorts of ways.

00:21:43.570 --> 00:21:44.764
You know, it's often--

00:21:44.764 --> 00:21:46.930
Stephen Jay Gould, who is
the evolutionary biologist

00:21:46.930 --> 00:21:50.500
at Harvard, described this kind
of story as "just so" stories,

00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:53.920
but also, just not that
useful a mode of explanation.

00:21:53.920 --> 00:21:56.560
As I was suggesting earlier,
you look back at advice columns

00:21:56.560 --> 00:22:00.040
from 1905, and they say
totally different things

00:22:00.040 --> 00:22:01.690
to what we say now
about who should

00:22:01.690 --> 00:22:04.390
take the initiative in
a courtship situation

00:22:04.390 --> 00:22:05.320
or whose role it is.

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:09.310
So I think that humans are
much stranger and more flexible

00:22:09.310 --> 00:22:11.069
than this kind of
narrative suggests.

00:22:11.069 --> 00:22:12.610
And it's really
comforting sometimes.

00:22:12.610 --> 00:22:13.568
I think, it's kind of--

00:22:13.568 --> 00:22:15.970
ev psych narratives are
comforting to everybody.

00:22:15.970 --> 00:22:20.020
If you are a conservative
in certain gender beliefs,

00:22:20.020 --> 00:22:22.502
it's reassuring to
think, like, oh, things

00:22:22.502 --> 00:22:23.460
won't change that much.

00:22:23.460 --> 00:22:25.750
This is how people are.

00:22:25.750 --> 00:22:29.020
And if you're frustrated
by the lack of progress,

00:22:29.020 --> 00:22:31.380
it's like, your
boyfriend is not a jerk.

00:22:31.380 --> 00:22:35.380
He evolved not to pick up
the dry cleaning, you know?

00:22:35.380 --> 00:22:36.880
So I think that
these narratives are

00:22:36.880 --> 00:22:38.290
very appealing as click bait.

00:22:38.290 --> 00:22:40.300
But I think that
they don't really,

00:22:40.300 --> 00:22:41.860
they're not very
useful, actually,

00:22:41.860 --> 00:22:43.840
in terms of their
explanatory power.

00:22:43.840 --> 00:22:45.280
And there have
been many critiques

00:22:45.280 --> 00:22:49.340
within academia of evolutionary
psychology specifically.

00:22:49.340 --> 00:22:49.840
It's funny.

00:22:49.840 --> 00:22:52.780
