the person seemed
interested, but they

00:30:23.990 --> 00:30:25.610
don't get to the
point where, did they

00:30:25.610 --> 00:30:27.230
like that person or not.

00:30:27.230 --> 00:30:29.480
And I try to get
them to that point.

00:30:29.480 --> 00:30:31.730
But it's interesting that
our brains don't naturally

00:30:31.730 --> 00:30:32.950
say, what do I want?

00:30:32.950 --> 00:30:35.829
It's what should I want or
how can I get them to want me?

00:30:35.829 --> 00:30:36.620
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah.

00:30:36.620 --> 00:30:38.330
LOGAN URY: So it's something
we're working through.

00:30:38.330 --> 00:30:39.371
MOIRA WEIGEL: Absolutely.

00:30:39.371 --> 00:30:40.400
LOGAN URY: Yeah.

00:30:40.400 --> 00:30:42.050
So we've talked a
lot about how dating

00:30:42.050 --> 00:30:45.095
is this arena where people
play out these gender roles.

00:30:45.095 --> 00:30:47.540
And we have these
scripts we've inherited,

00:30:47.540 --> 00:30:51.380
whether it's through books
or culture or movies.

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:54.920
If people in this room
or people watching online

00:30:54.920 --> 00:30:58.590
want to flip those scripts, what
are some things that we can do?

00:30:58.590 --> 00:30:59.340
MOIRA WEIGEL: Wow.

00:30:59.340 --> 00:31:02.147
I really do think
a recurring theme

00:31:02.147 --> 00:31:03.980
that I came across in
the different areas is

00:31:03.980 --> 00:31:09.020
that despite this tendency
of the self-help industry

00:31:09.020 --> 00:31:11.510
to mystify men and women
to each other, actually

00:31:11.510 --> 00:31:13.850
most humans want
more similar things.

00:31:13.850 --> 00:31:17.810
You know, most humans want some
combination of sex and intimacy

00:31:17.810 --> 00:31:19.710
and respect and communication.

00:31:19.710 --> 00:31:23.600
And I think that one of
the most harmful scripts

00:31:23.600 --> 00:31:26.750
is this idea that men and
women are essentially at odds

00:31:26.750 --> 00:31:28.610
and that all gender
and sexual relations

00:31:28.610 --> 00:31:33.350
are this sad compromise
of women, for whom sex

00:31:33.350 --> 00:31:36.770
is like work, and for men, it's
like recreation or something.

00:31:36.770 --> 00:31:38.460
But that's a whole other topic.

00:31:38.460 --> 00:31:41.870
So I think that it's
really important

00:31:41.870 --> 00:31:44.690
to get out of that script.

00:31:44.690 --> 00:31:47.420
And I think, yeah,
I don't know, I

00:31:47.420 --> 00:31:50.835
think there's so much
gamification there.

00:31:50.835 --> 00:31:52.710
This idea that it's a
game where you master--

00:31:52.710 --> 00:31:54.168
I mean, "The Rules"
and "The Game,"

00:31:54.168 --> 00:31:58.560
these are the two most
successful dating franchises

00:31:58.560 --> 00:32:00.060
of the past decade or so.

00:32:00.060 --> 00:32:05.570
But I think that trying
to get beyond these games

00:32:05.570 --> 00:32:08.690
and this idea that partners
are mysterious to one another

00:32:08.690 --> 00:32:12.080
and do this slightly more
challenging emotional work

00:32:12.080 --> 00:32:14.270
of being in touch
with one's own desires

00:32:14.270 --> 00:32:16.940
is the most fundamentally
important thing.

00:32:16.940 --> 00:32:19.250
And scripts-- I mean,
in some of the research

00:32:19.250 --> 00:32:23.104
that I cover on hookup
culture, it's so funny.

00:32:23.104 --> 00:32:24.770
You get these young
men again and again,

00:32:24.770 --> 00:32:27.830
saying, well, I imagine everyone
else is having so much sex.

00:32:27.830 --> 00:32:30.500
And I feel sad, but I
shouldn't, because I'm a man.

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:32.492
And this is what men
are supposed to want.

00:32:32.492 --> 00:32:34.700
And it's, like, first of
all, none of your classmates

00:32:34.700 --> 00:32:36.590
are having as much
sex as you think

00:32:36.590 --> 00:32:39.200
they are, or very few of them.

00:32:39.200 --> 00:32:42.170
And second of all, you
can't should about a want.

00:32:42.170 --> 00:32:43.820
You know, if you
feel sad about this,

00:32:43.820 --> 00:32:45.528
and you feel you
shouldn't because you're

00:32:45.528 --> 00:32:48.380
supposed to be masculine
and it's not masculine,

00:32:48.380 --> 00:32:50.510
that belief, again, about
this absolute gender

00:32:50.510 --> 00:32:53.299
difference and different aims is
producing a lot of unhappiness.

00:32:53.299 --> 00:32:55.340
It's actually very
counterproductive for everyone

00:32:55.340 --> 00:32:56.540
involved.

00:32:56.540 --> 00:32:58.790
LOGAN URY: Do you feel
optimistic about the generation

00:32:58.790 --> 00:32:59.900
younger than us?

00:32:59.900 --> 00:33:01.280
MOIRA WEIGEL:
Yeah, I think I do.

00:33:01.280 --> 00:33:01.939
I think I do.

00:33:01.939 --> 00:33:03.230
I think the kids are all right.

00:33:03.230 --> 00:33:06.020
I think that we
always have to think

00:33:06.020 --> 00:33:08.100
about class difference
and geographic differences

00:33:08.100 --> 00:33:10.190
and it's very hard
to generalize.

00:33:10.190 --> 00:33:11.810
But I think the
generation below us

00:33:11.810 --> 00:33:14.690
has better gender and
sexual politics than I

00:33:14.690 --> 00:33:16.010
did at their age, anyway.

00:33:16.010 --> 00:33:19.310
I think that there's a way in
which the internet is creating

00:33:19.310 --> 00:33:22.820
new kinds of discourse
and awareness.

00:33:22.820 --> 00:33:26.180
I think that there is,
despite the depressing state

00:33:26.180 --> 00:33:29.330
of affairs, this apocalyptic,
smoky state of affairs

00:33:29.330 --> 00:33:31.520
in America, generally,
there's a lot

00:33:31.520 --> 00:33:33.565
to feel hopeful about
with young people.

00:33:33.565 --> 00:33:35.690
LOGAN URY: Well, since you
are on a college campus,

00:33:35.690 --> 00:33:38.510
and in fact, the college campus
that you and I attended--

00:33:38.510 --> 00:33:39.510
MOIRA WEIGEL: It's true.

00:33:39.510 --> 00:33:42.470
LOGAN URY: --I would be curious
to see whether women who are

00:33:42.470 --> 00:33:44.090
undergrads right
now, whether they've

00:33:44.090 --> 00:33:48.110
been affected by sort of what
you called the Beyonce 2013

00:33:48.110 --> 00:33:50.210
feminism.

00:33:50.210 --> 00:33:52.010
So basically,
either on one hand,

00:33:52.010 --> 00:33:54.930
they are more feminist than we
were when we were in college,

00:33:54.930 --> 00:33:56.600
or it's just an age
thing and maybe they

00:33:56.600 --> 00:33:58.160
will reach that
point of identifying

00:33:58.160 --> 00:33:59.032
as a feminist later.

00:33:59.032 --> 00:33:59.990
MOIRA WEIGEL: I think--

00:33:59.990 --> 00:34:01.280
I suspect some
people in this room

00:34:01.280 --> 00:34:03.321
might be younger than I
am, so we could ask them.

00:34:03.321 --> 00:34:06.410
But I think that feminism
is trendier than it

00:34:06.410 --> 00:34:10.489
was when we were in college,
that this idea, I can't think

00:34:10.489 --> 00:34:12.780
if I have any hard
numbers to prove this,

00:34:12.780 --> 00:34:16.159
but when I think of when I
encounter young women now

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:17.790
who are in college
or around that age,

00:34:17.790 --> 00:34:19.090
they think it's cool
to be a feminist.

00:34:19.090 --> 00:34:20.810
And that's a thing
they identify as.

00:34:20.810 --> 00:34:26.449
I think that Beyonce and Hillary
and Sheryl and all these women

00:34:26.449 --> 00:34:29.690
helped produce that moment,
which I think is basically--

00:34:29.690 --> 00:34:32.300
Chimamanda Nazi Adichie--
that we should all

00:34:32.300 --> 00:34:35.060
be feminists moment that that
really resonated, which I think

00:34:35.060 --> 00:34:36.920
is basically a great thing.

00:34:36.920 --> 00:34:40.814
I think that there
are limitations to--

00:34:40.814 --> 00:34:42.980
I don't know, sort of the
transformation of feminism

00:34:42.980 --> 00:34:44.540
into a lifestyle
brand, or that it's

00:34:44.540 --> 00:34:47.920
this thing that you can just
make a choice individually

00:34:47.920 --> 00:34:50.030
to be this way and
that that will fix all

00:34:50.030 --> 00:34:51.312
the problems that women face.

00:34:51.312 --> 00:34:53.020
I think that there
are limitations to it.

00:34:53.020 --> 00:34:56.739
But basically, the kids
are more politically aware,

00:34:56.739 --> 00:34:59.840
more politically engaged, maybe,
than we were at their age,

00:34:59.840 --> 00:35:02.090
certainly around these
questions of gender.

00:35:02.090 --> 00:35:02.480
LOGAN URY: That's great.

00:35:02.480 --> 00:35:04.104
Yeah, I do find that
really comforting.

00:35:04.104 --> 00:35:07.010
And this idea that there
is more gender fluidity

00:35:07.010 --> 00:35:09.110
and flipping the
scripts and that people

00:35:09.110 --> 00:35:11.810
at least, whether or not
feminism is being commodified

00:35:11.810 --> 00:35:14.750
in some ways, it's at least
giving people the space

00:35:14.750 --> 00:35:17.030
to say like, hey, maybe we
shouldn't wear really short

00:35:17.030 --> 00:35:19.490
skirts so we can get
into that final club

00:35:19.490 --> 00:35:20.739
and see if we're on the list.

00:35:20.739 --> 00:35:21.530
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah.

00:35:21.530 --> 00:35:23.416
I think that that
does feel, again,

00:35:23.416 --> 00:35:25.040
there's a lot more
work to do, but that

00:35:25.040 --> 00:35:27.066
feels like a basic improvement.

00:35:27.066 --> 00:35:29.720
I think it wasn't even a
conversation my friends

00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:32.420
and I were having when
we were undergrads,

00:35:32.420 --> 00:35:35.570
at least not with
the same explicitness

00:35:35.570 --> 00:35:37.230
and emphaticness
that we see now.

00:35:37.230 --> 00:35:39.820
LOGAN URY: Or it was the
idea from from 9:00 to 5:00,

00:35:39.820 --> 00:35:42.650
you were in class, and you were
killing it and answering all

00:35:42.650 --> 00:35:43.890
the questions and doing well.

00:35:43.890 --> 00:35:46.310
But then, what happened at
night was a different part

00:35:46.310 --> 00:35:47.210
of your personality.

00:35:47.210 --> 00:35:49.880
And my hope would be that
people are more unified

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:52.280
in being that strong
woman during the day

00:35:52.280 --> 00:35:53.139
and in the evening.

00:35:53.139 --> 00:35:53.930
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah.

00:35:53.930 --> 00:35:55.090
I think what's
perverse, again, we

00:35:55.090 --> 00:35:56.160
were both undergrads at Harvard.

00:35:56.160 --> 00:35:57.576
And I imagine a
lot of people here

00:35:57.576 --> 00:36:01.070
are also a certain kind of type
that we saw a lot in college.

00:36:01.070 --> 00:36:04.100
I think what's hard is that we
were very conditioned to want

00:36:04.100 --> 00:36:05.600
to succeed and get approval.

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:08.720
And you get that for one set
of things, professionally

00:36:08.720 --> 00:36:11.750
or academically, and you get it
for a different set of things,

00:36:11.750 --> 00:36:13.110
socially and sexually.

00:36:13.110 --> 00:36:14.690
And so there's no
real contradiction

00:36:14.690 --> 00:36:17.120
between being the
straight A student who

00:36:17.120 --> 00:36:20.370
wears a teeny, tiny skirt and
stands outside the finals club

00:36:20.370 --> 00:36:20.870
at night.

00:36:20.870 --> 00:36:23.480
They're both ways
of seeking approval

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:25.430
from institutions of authority.

00:36:25.430 --> 00:36:28.490
And the men own the real estate
for the finals clubs, too.

00:36:28.490 --> 00:36:32.450
I mean, there's this deeply
gendered system of social power

00:36:32.450 --> 00:36:34.504
that we were really
responding to.

00:36:34.504 --> 00:36:35.670
It wasn't just in our heads.

00:36:35.670 --> 00:36:38.150
So it's this weird way that
it's like you're overachieving

00:36:38.150 --> 00:36:40.880
by being what someone else
wants, whether it's on your CV

00:36:40.880 --> 00:36:44.852
and about a boss or a teacher,
or about looking cute at night.

00:36:44.852 --> 00:36:47.060
And I think that it takes
a lot of personal strength,

00:36:47.060 --> 00:36:49.910
and also political solidarity
in these more collective forms

00:36:49.910 --> 00:36:52.080
of thinking, to change that.

00:36:52.080 --> 00:36:53.330
And I do think it's happening.

00:36:53.330 --> 00:36:54.230
LOGAN URY: I love
that perspective.

00:36:54.230 --> 00:36:55.940
Yeah, I think it's hard
for an 18-year-old,

00:36:55.940 --> 00:36:57.981
or certainly would have
been hard for me, to say,

00:36:57.981 --> 00:37:00.300
oh, success during the day
is doing well in my classes

00:37:00.300 --> 00:37:02.629
and success at night is
standing up to the patriarchy.

00:37:02.629 --> 00:37:03.420
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah?

00:37:03.420 --> 00:37:04.790
Well, hopefully, we
can make standing up

00:37:04.790 --> 00:37:05.927
to the patriarchy cool.

00:37:05.927 --> 00:37:07.010
I think it's already cool.

00:37:07.010 --> 00:37:08.300
LOGAN URY: On its way, yeah.

00:37:08.300 --> 00:37:11.327
So I do want to leave time for
questions from the audience.

00:37:11.327 --> 00:37:13.910
Before we get to that, I'm going
to ask you one more question.

00:37:13.910 --> 00:37:16.160
So this is something
I ask all my guests

00:37:16.160 --> 00:37:18.350
who join me for these
talks at Google.

00:37:18.350 --> 00:37:22.040
There is the Google.com home
page that has the Google logo.

00:37:22.040 --> 00:37:23.480
And then underneath
it sometimes,

00:37:23.480 --> 00:37:25.440
there's this line of text.

00:37:25.440 --> 00:37:28.700
So if you could write the
line of text for one day

00:37:28.700 --> 00:37:30.710
and millions of
people would see it

00:37:30.710 --> 00:37:33.020
as they do their
billions of searches,

00:37:33.020 --> 00:37:35.420
what would you put
on that line of text?

00:37:35.420 --> 00:37:38.330
And since this is a modern
romance talk, maybe what would

00:37:38.330 --> 00:37:41.347
that line be to help people with
their dating and relationships?

00:37:41.347 --> 00:37:42.430
MOIRA WEIGEL: Oh, my gosh.

00:37:42.430 --> 00:37:43.380
LOGAN URY: Yeah, no
pressure, though.

00:37:43.380 --> 00:37:44.520
MOIRA WEIGEL: No pressure.

00:37:44.520 --> 00:37:46.710
I think, because I
usually think of Google

00:37:46.710 --> 00:37:47.960
with those wonderful drawings.

00:37:47.960 --> 00:37:49.640
LOGAN URY: Oh, yeah,
we do have drawings.

00:37:49.640 --> 00:37:50.420
MOIRA WEIGEL: --when I look.

00:37:50.420 --> 00:37:51.753
I'm a terrible drawer, actually.

00:37:51.753 --> 00:37:54.380
LOGAN URY: You could commission
a Google Doodle for something

00:37:54.380 --> 00:37:55.280
that's on your mind.

00:37:55.280 --> 00:37:56.750
MOIRA WEIGEL: No, I've
been thinking a lot--

00:37:56.750 --> 00:37:58.614
and again, I feel like
we've just scratched

00:37:58.614 --> 00:37:59.780
the surface of this history.

00:37:59.780 --> 00:38:03.020
But I've been thinking a lot
about the leftist and feminist

00:38:03.020 --> 00:38:07.062
slogan, "None of us are free
until all of us are free."

00:38:07.062 --> 00:38:09.020
And that might seem like
a stretch from dating.

00:38:09.020 --> 00:38:13.040
But I think that there's
a way in which we

00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:15.827
can have fun at romance,
and we're not always

00:38:15.827 --> 00:38:17.660
supposed to be thinking
about the structural

00:38:17.660 --> 00:38:18.410
and the political.

00:38:18.410 --> 00:38:19.975
But men and women,
and again, we've

00:38:19.975 --> 00:38:21.350
hardly talked
about queer dating,

00:38:21.350 --> 00:38:23.970
which is the funnest part of
dating history, by the way.

00:38:23.970 --> 00:38:26.137
But I think that we can't--

00:38:26.137 --> 00:38:28.220
it's all very well to say
that we're more flexible

00:38:28.220 --> 00:38:30.678
and that we're more permissive
about romantic relationships

00:38:30.678 --> 00:38:32.500
and family structures
and all these things.

00:38:32.500 --> 00:38:34.940
But men and women
can't really meet

00:38:34.940 --> 00:38:37.970
as full romantic
equals until we address

00:38:37.970 --> 00:38:41.339
these kinds of underlying
social and structural problems.

00:38:41.339 --> 00:38:42.880
So again, there's
sort of these two--

00:38:42.880 --> 00:38:45.129
there's always this double
vision between the personal

00:38:45.129 --> 00:38:46.130
and the social.

00:38:46.130 --> 00:38:48.354
But I think that the
idea that none of us

00:38:48.354 --> 00:38:50.270
are sexy until all of
us are sexy, "none of us

00:38:50.270 --> 00:38:51.740
are free until all
of us are free"

00:38:51.740 --> 00:38:53.750
is a sentiment I've been
thinking about a lot.

00:38:53.750 --> 00:38:56.049
So that's my grand
claim to stake

00:38:56.049 --> 00:38:57.590
on the bottom of
the Google homepage.

00:38:57.590 --> 00:38:58.010
LOGAN URY: I love that.

00:38:58.010 --> 00:38:59.570
Well, maybe somebody
out here today

00:38:59.570 --> 00:39:00.932
can actually get that on there.

00:39:00.932 --> 00:39:01.890
MOIRA WEIGEL: Oh, yeah.

00:39:01.890 --> 00:39:02.150
LOGAN URY: OK.

00:39:02.150 --> 00:39:04.441
So now we'll open it up to
questions from the audience.

00:39:04.441 --> 00:39:06.417
And Scott has a handheld mic.

00:39:06.417 --> 00:39:08.750
AUDIENCE: I'm really interested
to hear your perspective

00:39:08.750 --> 00:39:12.650
on race within dating,
race or ethnicity.

00:39:12.650 --> 00:39:14.570
I recently heard
a podcast on NPR

00:39:14.570 --> 00:39:17.900
about dating apps and how
it's completely skewed when

00:39:17.900 --> 00:39:19.430
it comes to race.

00:39:19.430 --> 00:39:22.640
And throughout history or just
what your perspective on it

00:39:22.640 --> 00:39:24.099
is now in current times.

00:39:24.099 --> 00:39:24.890
MOIRA WEIGEL: Yeah.

00:39:24.890 --> 00:39:28.100
I mean, this is a great
question, and a huge question.

00:39:28.100 --> 00:39:30.020
I think that there
is all this data.

00:39:30.020 --> 00:39:32.353
And one thing that's interesting
about the proliferation

00:39:32.353 --> 00:39:34.850
of these apps is it
does give us much more

00:39:34.850 --> 00:39:38.030
measurable information
about people's preferences

00:39:38.030 --> 00:39:38.940
and behaviors.

00:39:38.940 --> 00:39:42.200
There's certainly a lot of
disappointing information

00:39:42.200 --> 00:39:44.690
that's come out of
OkCupid and other apps

00:39:44.690 --> 00:39:48.740
in terms of how forms of social
prejudice that we see elsewhere

00:39:48.740 --> 00:39:51.967
in society play out in dating.

00:39:51.967 --> 00:39:53.300
There are so many things to say.

00:39:53.300 --> 00:39:55.700
I mean, historically, one
thing that's really interesting

00:39:55.700 --> 00:39:58.040
is that dating as
a practice really

00:39:58.040 --> 00:40:02.150
emerges out of the working
class in the early 20th century.

00:40:02.150 --> 00:40:04.850
And so you have these
really vibrant dating

00:40:04.850 --> 00:40:07.250
and nightlife cultures in
the Harlem Renaissance,

00:40:07.250 --> 00:40:07.920
for instance.

00:40:07.920 --> 00:40:11.499
Or you have a really vibrant
queer dating culture.

00:40:11.499 --> 00:40:12.790
We didn't even talk about this.

00:40:12.790 --> 00:40:14.164
This is one of my
favorite facts,

00:40:14.164 --> 00:40:17.242
how TGI Friday's, which
was the first singles' bar,

00:40:17.242 --> 00:40:18.950
was invented because
the entrepreneur who

00:40:18.950 --> 00:40:21.590
started it was, like, we need
a gay bar for straight people.

00:40:21.590 --> 00:40:22.286
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:22.286 --> 00:40:23.660
MOIRA WEIGEL:
