00:51:11.960 --> 00:51:14.750
queer dating has not
been legible as dating

00:51:14.750 --> 00:51:16.122
to most of society.

00:51:16.122 --> 00:51:18.080
At the same time, and
perhaps not incidentally,

00:51:18.080 --> 00:51:21.170
it's also been like the funnest
and most experimental and best,

00:51:21.170 --> 00:51:24.260
and best place, freed of
these terrible, gendered norms

00:51:24.260 --> 00:51:26.550
that we see across
so much other dating.

00:51:26.550 --> 00:51:29.660
So I think that in my book
there are two chapters that deal

00:51:29.660 --> 00:51:32.420
primarily with LGBTQ dating.

00:51:32.420 --> 00:51:34.910
And I think that it often--

00:51:34.910 --> 00:51:38.440
the first one deals a
lot with the roaring '20s

00:51:38.440 --> 00:51:40.340
and the '30s and
speakeasy scenes

00:51:40.340 --> 00:51:43.130
and these spaces that
are at once theoretically

00:51:43.130 --> 00:51:45.920
out of the public eye,
but then also become

00:51:45.920 --> 00:51:50.300
an avant garde or lead what's
fashionable for dating.

00:51:50.300 --> 00:51:52.670
You see it again, as I was
suggesting, in the '60s,

00:51:52.670 --> 00:51:54.950
with this hilarious
guy Alan Stillman, who

00:51:54.950 --> 00:51:57.470
starts TGI Friday's and is,
like, if we could scale this

00:51:57.470 --> 00:52:00.310
for straight people, we'd
make a bazillion dollars,

00:52:00.310 --> 00:52:01.460
as indeed, he did.

00:52:01.460 --> 00:52:05.780
But I think that often you see
cultures of experimentation

00:52:05.780 --> 00:52:10.130
not burdened by these norms
about what I keep joking about,

00:52:10.130 --> 00:52:12.410
this idea that men and
women are inevitably at odds

00:52:12.410 --> 00:52:16.040
and that sex is this depressing
compromise, that allow

00:52:16.040 --> 00:52:17.307
for a lot more possibility.

00:52:17.307 --> 00:52:19.640
I think because there aren't,
or for most of the history

00:52:19.640 --> 00:52:22.730
of dating, haven't been such
overbearing social scripts

00:52:22.730 --> 00:52:25.010
about how men are and
how women are-- you know,

00:52:25.010 --> 00:52:27.590
LGBTQ folks don't have to deal
with those in the same way--

00:52:27.590 --> 00:52:31.730
that often you see much
more self-awareness

00:52:31.730 --> 00:52:34.947
or thoughtfulness about defining
desires and expectations,

00:52:34.947 --> 00:52:36.530
because there aren't
these assumptions

00:52:36.530 --> 00:52:39.140
about what they should be.

00:52:39.140 --> 00:52:41.870
I think one part of the book
deals a lot with the AIDS

00:52:41.870 --> 00:52:44.360
crisis and the safe sex
movement, too, and the ways

00:52:44.360 --> 00:52:49.160
in which really heroic
activists around HIV and AIDS

00:52:49.160 --> 00:52:51.980
started building materials
to help couples talk

00:52:51.980 --> 00:52:56.991
about sexual practices more
specifically and more openly,

00:52:56.991 --> 00:52:58.490
and how that became
really important

00:52:58.490 --> 00:53:01.840
for people of all
genders and orientations.

00:53:01.840 --> 00:53:08.580
So I think that queer dating
in my book and in history

00:53:08.580 --> 00:53:10.590
is often a space of
greater experimentation

00:53:10.590 --> 00:53:13.760
and self-awareness and
then often sets the trends.

00:53:13.760 --> 00:53:17.030
In the same way you get TGI
Friday's imitating gay bars,

00:53:17.030 --> 00:53:19.640
you get Tender imitating Grindr.

00:53:19.640 --> 00:53:23.516
So it gets sort of
co-opted and made less fun

00:53:23.516 --> 00:53:24.640
for straight people, maybe.

00:53:24.640 --> 00:53:27.050
But those are a couple of
themes that come to mind.

